sec.sch: ^^REV HARRISON WEBB'S COLORED PRIVATE SCH BALTIMORE MD

misc: Was an infant when his mother was bought from her owners by her mother.  After attending Rev. Webb's private school in Baltimore, hired himself out to the US Navy; was ward-room boy on the "Saranac"; was discharged after a 3-year cruise in the Mediterranean; shipped next on the "St. Lawrence" and cruised to the coast of Brazil; in 1861, shipped on the military transport "Potomac"; transferred to the transport "City of New York", plying between New York City, the Army of the Potomac, and Hilton Head, SC.  In 1877, after graduating in medicine, he went to the Mendi Mission, West Africa, as physician with a corps of colored missionaries; undertook this post at the suggestion of William E. Dodge of New York City, who had been one of his benefactors.  When his wife and newborn child died in Africa, he sent his other two children back to Baltimore, where he also returned shortly afterwards.  Practiced medicine in various locations in SC.  Was settled in Jonesville, but had to relocate to Hardeeville as a result of disaster to rice crops.  In Hardeeville, his house was destroyed by fire, 14 Dec. 1898:  "Through the kindness of white and colored friends, I have been enabled to continue my practice almost without the usual interruptions peculiar to such an accident."
